Thanks for your kind words. I am sorry your friend had to go through this and I think it says a lot about you that you put aside your pro-life feelings and supported her during what I know is a very tough time. I'm sure your other friend has her reasons for going to term and she has every right to make that choice.<br>
<br>
However, I do have to challenge you on something. You said &quot;I wish there were stricter laws on abortion, such as making it legal on the cases of rape, incest or the mothers life is in danger.&quot; <br>
<br>
Abortion is legal in these case now. But as a pro-lifer who wants abortion outlawed, why do you value these exceptions? Is the fetus less human or less valuable in these cases? Or is it because these cases present too much of a hardship for the mother? <br>
<br>
If it's about hardship, what about a mother who already has more children than she can support, or will be on bedrest the entire pregnancy, or will lose her job or whose marriage will crumble, or will be suicidal because she can't take her anti-depression meds or is very young and not ready for motherhood or the trauma of giving a baby away? (I could NEVER give a baby away, could you? How can we force this on teens?) Are these not undue hardships? Do you really want lawmakers making one-size-fits-all decisions about what constitutes hardship pregnancy?<br>
<br>
If it's not hardship that concerns you, is it that in these cases the woman did not choose sex? If so, then aren't you saying that pregnancy is a just punishment for sex? I hear pro-lifers (usually males) saying &quot;she shoulda kept her legs crossed if she didn't want a kid.&quot; Last night on Donahue, Phillis Schaffly said &quot;I didn't get them pregnant!&quot; So, if women who &quot;choose&quot; sex and have a birth control failure, or even get caught up in the moment and end up PG, are to be punished by pregnancy, what about the GUY? Should he be let off the hook? Why can't we throw him in the slammer or at least have him castrated?<br>
<br>
If any of your answers have to do with &quot;what god wants&quot; then please also explain how that fits in with separation of church and state?<br>
<br>
Paige, you seem like a very nice lady so don't take this post as mean spirited. I just want you to think these issues through all the way to the back before you throw your support behind truncating women's rights.  <br>
<br>
DL <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rhinosmom>rhinosmom</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://mjkingbird.homestead.com/files/paige.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 109<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/9/03 12:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=54.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: for pro-lifers</span><hr size=1> DL, thanks for calling me pro-life and not anti-choice! I really hate that term!<br>
<br>
I think that no matter what system we have, there are and will be flaws and someone is going to get a raw deal. It may be the baby or it may be the mother.<br>
<br>
I know that it is legal in the cases I stated. I do wish is was more restrictive. It's such a complicated thing. As a religious person, I know God cherishes these little ones. But I also know that he gives us free agency. I wish neither was compromised!<br>
<br>
In cases of the mothers health and such, no, the fetus is no less life or valuble. But, if the mother were to die, I think &quot;What good would that do?&quot; The fetus would then die also.<br>
<br>
As far as hardships....part of being a mother is putting your child first. If you were not able to care for that child, though it might be painful for the mother, she would need to think of her child first. I still think adoption is better than killing the child because you couldn't deal with giving it away. How is THAT a better deal for the child????? We have friends that adopted a beautiful baby girl last year. I see the thrill they have with her and how her FOUR big brothers adore her. That baby has a WONDERFUL life. The mother was 20, unwed and not prepared to mother. She gave the baby and that family a wonderful gift. I have a friend from HS that gave her baby up. We were out of HS and she was married, but it was turning into an abusive relationship. She did a selfless thing by setting HER feelings aside and doing the best she could for her child.<br>
