&quot;The most important work you will ever do will be within the walls of your own home.&quot; </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=luvthatdyl>LuvThatDyl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/9/03 12:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=54.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  abortion</span><hr size=1> This is a subject that really gets me started.  I am pro-choice, as I stated below.  This doesn't mean that I take abortion lightly, or that I would choose it for myself, except maybe for extenuating circumstances.  Actually, I can't really say for sure which situations I would or wouldn't have an abortion because I am not in those situations, and neither are the lawmakers that want to outlaw Roe v Wade.  I have never been raped, I have never been pg with an unhealthy baby (unless you count my miscarriage) and I didn't get into trouble as a teenager.  I am very fortunate, but just because I've been fortunate, that doesn't mean that I have the right to force other women to give birth.<br>
<br>
I have heard people say that abortion should only be legal in cases of rape or medical necessity.  Well, my question is:  how do we know when these instances have occurred?  Take rape for instance.  At what point does the law decide a woman has been raped and allow her to abort?  Is it when she is brought into the hospital?  Do we need to wait for a conviction?  How exactly is our system supposed to monitor something like that?  Medical necessity isn't so black and white either.  There was a case in Louisiana where a woman had a health condition that would put her life in danger if she took her pg to term, and she needed state funds for the abortion.  The state turned her down because the doctor said there was a 50-50 chance of survival, and the court determined that the risk of death wasn't high enough to give her the funds for the abortion.  I don't know what ended up happening to the woman, but I don't want lawmakers playing Russian Roulette with my life like that.  <br>
<br>
I also take issue when people condemn women who weren't raped or who don't have medical issues.  We have so many unwanted children in this world who are hungry and lacking proper care.  Why bring more unwanted children into this?  Yes, people should be careful and behave responsibly when it comes to sex, but sex is a natural urge, and people sometimes make mistakes.  Our law would allow a 15 year old to get out of a written contract because her age makes her incompetent to take on such a responsibility.  Yet we want this same 15 year old girl to become a parent?  Why is she too immature to take responsibility for a car loan, but not a child?  <br>
<br>
Then there is the adoption issue.  I really do respect women who make that selfless decision, but it isn't practical for everyone.  I won't even get into the emotional aspects of it.  I'll just stick with the practical aspects of it since that is the only thing lawmakers seem to understand.  Who is going to pay for this girl's prenatal care?  Who is going to pay her rent when she has to keep leaving work to go to doctor's appointments?  What if she needs bed rest?  Who is going to pay to feed this woman while spending 8 weeks in bed?  A woman's body is not just a baby vending machine.  <br>
<br>
Now I know this all boils down to when life actually starts.  I admit that I felt a bond with both my babies right away.   I mourned the baby I miscarried for a long time, and I lost that baby at 11 weeks.  The baby just never formed, so I know there was no suffering or anything, but I felt attached to that baby anyway.  However, even in the case of my son who was and is a healthy boy, during early pregnancy the baby is just a mass of cells.  It is more in our minds because when we envision having a baby, we are envisioning a full-term baby, and not a mass of cells.  When a baby is still a mass of cells, they aren't going to know what is going on.  So yes, it is a life, but there are just certain cases where that baby might be better off being put out of their misery before they could think or feel.  I don't agree with late-term abortions unless there are medical reasons because I believe at that stage babies could think and feel.  While Clinton was in office the Dems tried to put a law on the books that would disallow late-term abortion unless there are medical reasons.  However, the Reps wouldn't allow it because a law like that would allow abortion in general, and if they don't want laws with any wording that would allow abortion at all.  There is a constant war between both parties because any law surrounding abortion would undermine the goals of the other side.  This is all the more reason why the decision needs to be kept with the person directly involved, the woman.<br>
<br>
Stacey <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rhinosmom>rhinosmom</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://mjkingbird.homestead.com/files/paige.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 112<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/9/03 12:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=54.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: abortion</span><hr size=1> That mass of cells has a heart beating about 20 days after conception. <p>Paige<br>
